  "text": "Godefroy and Shapiro proved that, for Hilbert spaces X, if 0 is a non-constant function such that 0(fi) PI 9D ^ 0, then the adjoint operator M^ satisfies the Hypercyclicity Criterion [13, Theorem 4.5]. Bonet, Domanski and Lindstrom [CITATION_1] Section 4] showed that the above condition is equivalent to the fact that the transpose multiplier M'^ is chaotic on X' -(H®)', the dual of the Banach space of analytic functions / on the disc such that the radial weight v and the product fv tend to zero at the boundary. Our goal is to show that every hypercyclic operator which is the transpose of a multiplication operator on X satisfies the Criterion. This also covers the adjoint multipliers when X is a Hilbert space. Under the specified assumptions on X we have the following result. A precise example is <j>(z) := z on the disc, as a multiplier of the Dirichlet space V of the unit disc, which consists of all functions / holomorphic on B> for which the derivative / ' is square integrable with respect to Lebesgue area measure. In this case M£ is the backward shift on the Bergman space A 2 , the space of holomorphic functions on D that are square integrable with respect to Lebesgue area measure, which is hypercyclic [CITATION_2] , but (/>(fi) does not intersect the unit circle.",
